historic events.

00:02:35.470 --> 00:02:40.540
Today is one of those chapters in
the great legacy of our country.

00:02:40.540 --> 00:02:45.200
I want to thank all of you
for your commitment to working

00:02:45.200 --> 00:02:49.330
for disabled Americans, especially
those in the deaf community,

00:02:49.330 --> 00:02:52.800
in Congress, in Gallaudet
and the rest

00:02:52.800 --> 00:02:55.400 position:56%
of academia, and the private sector.

00:02:55.400 --> 00:02:57.990
I'm proud to join all of you
in celebrating the Americans

00:02:57.990 --> 00:03:00.420
with Disabilities Act today.

00:03:00.420 --> 00:03:04.680
As we know, our nation was founded
on the principle that all people,

00:03:04.680 --> 00:03:06.750
men, women, are created equal.

00:03:06.750 --> 00:03:10.820
The ADA is a landmark piece
of legislation that embodied

00:03:10.820 --> 00:03:14.140 position:56%
that principle with its impact
making ripple effects throughout our

00:03:14.140 --> 00:03:17.820
nation still today benefiting
countless disabled Americans.

00:03:17.820 --> 00:03:22.900
It has helped open up doors,
both literally and figuratively,

00:03:22.900 --> 00:03:27.420 position:56%
to employment and services for many
people with disabilities and ensured

00:03:27.420 --> 00:03:30.360
that those with disabilities
are afforded equal access

00:03:30.360 --> 00:03:33.620
to government services
and public accommodations.

00:03:33.620 --> 00:03:36.920
It's hard to think of our
country without the ADA.

00:03:36.920 --> 00:03:41.210
It's hard to think of
America before that period

00:03:41.210 --> 00:03:43.650
and why that was ever the case.

00:03:43.650 --> 00:03:45.830
The ADA helped implement,
for example,

00:03:45.830 --> 00:03:48.890
in the deaf community
telecommunications relay services,

00:03:48.890 --> 00:03:50.790
making sure the deaf,
hard of hearing,

00:03:50.790 --> 00:03:53.330
can have full access
to telephone networks.

00:03:53.330 --> 00:03:55.850
These reforms were important steps
towards making sure that no one

00:03:55.850 --> 00:04:00.200
in America gets left behind and
everyone has equal opportunities.

00:04:00.200 --> 00:04:05.930
Now, I'm a Kansan, and Kansas has
a very special role in history

00:04:05.930 --> 00:04:10.690
when it comes to the ADA.

00:04:10.690 --> 00:04:13.710
That connection continues
today with the legacy left

00:04:13.710 --> 00:04:16.810
by a great statesman
known as Senator Bob Dole,

00:04:16.810 --> 00:04:20.190
who just recently had his
94th birthday, by the way.

00:04:20.190 --> 00:04:23.800
He was and still is one
of biggest advocates

00:04:23.800 --> 00:04:28.160
for the disability community,
inspiring myself and others

00:04:28.160 --> 00:04:32.300
to continue to carry the
baton and his legacy forward.

00:04:32.300 --> 00:04:35.980
He had such a special personal
story because as someone

00:04:35.980 --> 00:04:38.620
with a disability stemming
from injuries sustained

00:04:38.620 --> 00:04:42.480
in combat during World War II, he
was able to use his perspective

00:04:42.480 --> 00:04:46.490
to help fight for others,
to help fight for all of us.

00:04:46.490 --> 00:04:49.450
He was instrumental in the passage
of the ADA, and he viewed it as one

00:04:49.450 --> 00:04:54.430
of his proudest moments, and long
after Senator Dole and others,

00:04:54.430 --> 00:04:58.520
we've all passed in politics
his legacy, the ADA will pass

00:04:58.520 --> 00:05:00.860
on from generation to generation.

00:05:00.860 --> 00:05:02.340
He had a lot of proud moments.

00:05:02.340 --> 00:05:03.980
He did a lot of things,
but saying it was one

00:05:03.980 --> 00:05:06.590
of his proudest says a lot
considering his career.

00:05:06.590 --> 00:05:10.760
So his legacy is an inspiration to
me and many of our fellow Kansans.

00:05:10.760 --> 00:05:15.040
In my service in Congress, I
represent the Kansas School

00:05:15.040 --> 00:05:17.040
for the Deaf in Olathe, Kansas.

00:05:17.040 --> 00:05:20.340
I have had a great opportunity to
work with many of the students,

00:05:20.340 --> 00:05:24.990
teachers, and community members
who make up my constituents

00:05:24.990 --> 00:05:28.070
and who are a very important
part of our community,

00:05:28.070 --> 00:05:33.200
and so what Senator Dole laid
forward is what I'm working

00:05:33.200 --> 00:05:36.170
to fight for-to fight
for disability rights,

00:05:36.170 --> 00:05:39.300
and I think the Senator would agree
there's still more to be done.

00:05:39.300 --> 00:05:41.590
The difficult reality is that
in spite of the progress made

00:05:41.590 --> 00:05:44.250
through the ADA, around
seven in ten deaf people

00:05:44.250 --> 00:05:47.180
in the U.S. are unemployed
or under employed.

00:05:47.180 --> 00:05:49.260
We have a lot of work to do.

00:05:49.260 --> 00:05:50.970
This means that there are
33 million deaf people

00:05:50.970 --> 00:05:53.490
who can't make enough money
to support themselves.

00:05:53.490 --> 00:05:56.420
This is just one symptom that
shows that our work is not done

00:05:56.420 --> 00:05:59.670 position:56%
and there are clearly still barriers
between deaf people and quality jobs

00:05:59.670 --> 00:06:02.600
and full involvement in society.

00:06:02.600 --> 00:06:06.070 position:56%
We've attempted to partner with many
employers throughout the country

00:06:06.070 --> 00:06:10.040
to help them build
opportunities for employment.

00:06:10.040 --> 00:06:13.060
Just a few months ago there was an
event we had at the Kansas School

00:06:13.060 --> 00:06:17.030
for the Deaf with Uber, and they
were showing they have specific

00:06:17.030 --> 00:06:20.400
programs set up to help the deaf
community become Uber drivers,

00:06:20.400 --> 00:06:21.700
for example.

00:06:21.700 --> 00:06:24.940
So technology is also helping
us solve this problem along

00:06:24.940 --> 00:06:28.710
with government policy, but
in recognition of the need

00:06:28.710 --> 00:06:30.770
to keep advocating for
the deaf community,

00:06:30.770 --> 00:06:33.550
that was what led Congressman
Takano, my good friend

00:06:33.550 --> 00:06:36.450
from California, and I to help form

00:06:36.450 --> 00:06:38.570
and build the Congressional
Deaf Caucus.

00:06:38.570 --> 00:06:40.790
We've been joined by 18
other members of Congress

00:06:40.790 --> 00:06:44.580
who are all dedicated to advocating
on behalf of deaf Americans.

00:06:44.580 --> 00:06:46.470
The Congressional Deaf
Caucus recognized

00:06:46.470 --> 00:06:49.030
that the ADA was not the finish
line in disability rights,

00:06:49.030 --> 00:06:52.120
but rather one step as part of
an effort that needs to continue.

00:06:52.120 --> 00:06:57.860 position:56%
Now I also have another role in that
when I was first came to Congress,

00:06:57.860 --> 00:07:00.890
I was honored to be appointed
by the Speaker of the House

00:07:00.890 --> 00:07:06.300
