00:39:18.920 --> 00:39:20.930
We all want to feel a connection.

00:39:20.930 --> 00:39:28.380
That's natural, but that connection
is not something we can always see

00:39:28.380 --> 00:39:30.460
or hear.

00:39:30.460 --> 00:39:33.390
It's something that we can feel.

00:39:33.390 --> 00:39:35.180
There's something that
we feel in our heart.

00:39:35.180 --> 00:39:37.660
It's a moment of clarity.

00:39:37.660 --> 00:39:41.140
I discovered this when I was a
wee lad learning how to read.

00:39:41.140 --> 00:39:45.240
Even though sign language is
how I prefer to communicate,

00:39:45.240 --> 00:39:48.580
reading allows me to learn
more about the world.

00:39:50.710 --> 00:39:53.660
There's a lot you can
learn about the world just

00:39:53.660 --> 00:39:59.220 position:56%
by hearing it somewhere, like on the
radio when you're driving to work,

00:39:59.220 --> 00:40:02.750
or through the grapevine, which,
what I understand, is a polite way

00:40:02.750 --> 00:40:06.460
of saying that you've been
shamelessly eavesdropping.

00:40:06.460 --> 00:40:07.760
[Laughter] I don't
have that privilege

00:40:07.760 --> 00:40:12.120
to consciously absorb information
without actively pursuing it.

00:40:13.750 --> 00:40:15.870
That's not a burden for me.

00:40:15.870 --> 00:40:17.720
It's actually a blessing.

00:40:17.720 --> 00:40:21.990
What wasn't handed to me I've
wanted for myself with a passion,

00:40:21.990 --> 00:40:24.620
and that passion started when
I was in pre-kindergarten.

00:40:24.620 --> 00:40:33.190
We had a customary naptime,
which was never my cup of tea.

00:40:33.190 --> 00:40:35.170
Luckily one day my teacher told me

00:40:35.170 --> 00:40:36.900
that I didn't have
to naptime anymore.

00:40:36.900 --> 00:40:39.470 position:56%
Instead she took me into her office.

00:40:39.470 --> 00:40:43.620
She had piles of books, vocabulary
cards, and colorful pictures

00:40:43.620 --> 00:40:47.960
of everyday things, but I
didn't know the word for it.

00:40:47.960 --> 00:40:52.790
I felt like the cartoon man
sketched above the word excited.

00:40:52.790 --> 00:40:58.410
I was right there in my teacher's
office when I learned how to read.

00:40:58.410 --> 00:41:01.140
Learning to read was
a fascinating process.

00:41:01.140 --> 00:41:03.110 position:56%
Unless you know someone who is deaf,

00:41:03.110 --> 00:41:05.570
you've probably never considered
how an audible language can be

00:41:05.570 --> 00:41:06.900
taught visually.

00:41:06.900 --> 00:41:08.880
It usually takes four steps.

00:41:08.880 --> 00:41:12.830
My teacher would show me a drawing
of a hairy beast, and then letter

00:41:12.830 --> 00:41:15.420
by letter she spelt the
corresponding word in English

00:41:15.420 --> 00:41:18.720
and ASL, and then showed the sign.

00:41:18.720 --> 00:41:21.130
So I made the connection between
the written word, the paper,

00:41:21.130 --> 00:41:23.730
a finger spelling, and
ultimately a sign, and now I knew

00:41:23.730 --> 00:41:26.030
that hairy beast was a dog.

00:41:35.420 --> 00:41:38.800
That was essentially the
foundation for my reading skills,

00:41:38.800 --> 00:41:43.150
but there's one crucial
thing missing-my own voice,

00:41:43.150 --> 00:41:47.690
and what I mean by this is I was
mechanically competent in writing,

00:41:47.690 --> 00:41:52.210
but it was too precise, devoid
of any natural occurring humanity

00:41:52.210 --> 00:41:56.160
that is so apparent in everyone's
voice, both spoken and written.

00:41:56.160 --> 00:42:00.120
What I craved was to be able to
express myself as authentically

00:42:00.120 --> 00:42:04.450
as possible through writing,
which at that point was tricky

00:42:04.450 --> 00:42:06.340
because I couldn't hear
organic conversations

00:42:06.340 --> 00:42:08.690
and [inaudible] that organically.

00:42:08.690 --> 00:42:13.430
Fortunately, I discovered a book of
children's stories called "A Series

00:42:13.430 --> 00:42:18.690
of Unfortunate Events" by Lemony
Snicket in the third grade.

00:42:18.690 --> 00:42:23.680 position:56%
It was about the Baudelaire orphans.

00:42:23.680 --> 00:42:26.270
They lost their parents
in a terrible fire,

00:42:26.270 --> 00:42:31.610
and now their new guardian, Count
Olaf, is a vile egomaniac who lies

00:42:31.610 --> 00:42:37.250
to get whatever he wants, including
the orphans' enormous fortune.

00:42:37.250 --> 00:42:43.950
Snicket's writing style
is quite distinctive,

00:42:43.950 --> 00:42:49.340
which I would say means
easily recognizable due

00:42:49.340 --> 00:42:50.690
to the author's affinity

00:42:50.690 --> 00:42:53.060
for humorously defining
his large vocabulary

00:42:53.060 --> 00:42:55.710
in the middle of the story.

00:42:55.710 --> 00:42:58.270
For me, it was love at first word.

00:42:58.270 --> 00:43:01.670
Here was this book written
for children that had words

00:43:01.670 --> 00:43:07.200
like penultimate, standoffish,
words that you don't normally read,

00:43:07.200 --> 00:43:08.950
and his tone was interesting
as well.

00:43:08.950 --> 00:43:12.190
It was very funny and familiar.

00:43:12.190 --> 00:43:15.230
It was something that I want.

00:43:15.230 --> 00:43:19.110
So as I started to read
more through the series,

00:43:19.110 --> 00:43:24.180
I had a new dimension
added to my prism.

00:43:30.340 --> 00:43:34.150
One day I saw the world through
the eyes of a cynical New Yorker,

00:43:34.150 --> 00:43:37.860
David Sedaris, where a horrible
incident could be recounted

00:43:37.860 --> 00:43:40.840
as a darkly funny anecdote.

00:43:40.840 --> 00:43:44.830
The next day I'd see the world
through Atticus Finch's eyes

00:43:44.830 --> 00:43:49.620 position:56%
as a place to never lose hope when
it comes to fighting the good fight.

00:43:50.790 --> 00:43:53.260
Eventually my perspective
became an amalgamation

00:43:53.260 --> 00:43:56.810
of the books I read over the years.

00:43:56.810 --> 00:43:59.470
Reading the conversations
in these books was

00:43:59.470 --> 00:44:01.800
where I found a natural rhythm.

00:44:01.800 --> 00:44:07.830
That rhythm fermented from reading
the close captioning on TV shows

00:44:07.830 --> 00:44:13.230
like "30 Rock" and "Seinfeld" with
a cascade of rapid fire word play,

00:44:13.230 --> 00:44:16.860
and that was the humanity
I longed for in my writing.

00:44:16.860 --> 00:44:19.330
With a solid understanding
of the art of conversation

00:44:19.330 --> 00:44:22.410
in English, I found my voice.

00:44:25.130 --> 00:44:27.700
Throughout this journey
I never stopped reading.

00:44:27.700 --> 00:44:30.650
I learned to read about the world.

00:44:43.070 --> 00:44:48.300
The value of reading comes
from the power of information.

00:44:49.770 --> 00:44:55.800
I read to rid myself of
ignorance, and I can tell you

00:44:55.800 --> 00:45:01.350
that when you read only 140
characters, that's not enough.

00:45:05.400 --> 00:45:09.540
I don't want to come across as an
insufferable know-it-all but just

00:45:09.540 --> 00:45:12.180 position:56%
to show you how much I want to know.

00:45:19.050 --> 00:45:22.570
It's when people struggle
to find meaning in life

00:45:22.570 --> 00:45:24.330 position:56%
that I find meaning in the struggle.

00:45:24.330 --> 00:45:27.510
I have a purpose.

00:45:27.510 --> 00:45:31.530
It's why I get out of bed every
morning lusting for novelty

00:45:31.530 --> 00:45:34.040
where the adage goes "There's
a whole world out there waiting

00:45:34.040 --> 00:45:38.580 position:56%
for you," and I started exploring
that world by remaining in one place

00:45:38.580 --> 00:45:42.920
with the greatest ticket
ever, a book.

00:45:45.030 --> 00:45:49.450
In addition to falling
in love with books,

00:45:49.450 --> 00:45:54.380
because of the strides we made in
public education and civil rights,

00:45:54.380 --> 00:45:57.440
that disconnection
from the world I felt

00:45:58.620 --> 00:46:02.590
as a deaf person is
no longer tangible.

00:46:09.070 --> 00:46:12.890
To rest on our laurels and take
all our progress we've made

00:46:12.890 --> 00:46:16.860
in the last 20 years for granted
wouldn't just be a disservice

00:46:16.860 --> 00:46:18.530
to the trailblazers.

00:46:18.530 --> 00:46:20.630
It would be a disservice
to our children

00:46:20.630 --> 00:46:23.040
and our children's children.

00:46:23.040 --> 00:46:27.350
I'm here because I know
the world is bigger

00:46:27.350 --> 00:46:30.380
than this extraordinary nation.

00:46:30.380 --> 00:46:32.260
I'm here because I
know we won't rest

00:46:32.260 --> 00:46:36.140
until we leave the world a
better place than we found it,

00:46:36.140 --> 00:46:40.770
and all of this starts with
a willingness to be a student

00:46:40.770 --> 00:46:47.010
for life, and we can do that
just by opening a book and taking

00:46:47.010 --> 00:46:50.220
in that first sentence
